    <title>Twitch launches a dedicated ‘hot tubs’ category after advertiser pushback</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="" src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/M9nIAT9EbIaTLR-wU1rO943SWIE=/0x0:2463x1642/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/69325278/Screen_Shot_2021_05_21_at_3.08.21_PM.0.png" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;A screenshot of Twitch’s new hot tubs category.&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="7X1K7G"&gt;Twitch is launching a dedicated category for hot tub streams after claiming that it has received pushback from advertisers and viewers about how the trend has taken over the platform. The new “&lt;a href="https://www.twitch.tv/directory/game/Pools%2C%20Hot%20Tubs%2C%20and%20Beaches"&gt;Pools, Hot Tubs, and Beaches&lt;/a&gt;” category is meant to let creators stream what they want, while also giving Twitch advertisers a more convenient way to prevent ads from running on streams that they don’t approve of.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="qqfLdl"&gt;Earlier this week, &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2021/5/18/22442733/amouranth-twitch-ads-suspended-indefinitely"&gt;Twitch pulled advertising&lt;/a&gt; from some hot tub streamers without warning. In a statement sent to &lt;em&gt;The Verge &lt;/em&gt;today, the company said that was a mistake. “We did not alert impacted creators at the time, and we should have–our creators rely on us,” a spokesperson said. Twitch said the ads were suspended at advertisers’ request...&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;
    &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2021/5/21/22447898/twitch-hot-tub-category-launches-amouranth-advertising"&gt;Continue reading&amp;hellip;&lt;/a&gt;
  &lt;/p&gt;

</content>
