    <title>Citizen, the vigilante justice app, has a plan to deploy private security forces, too</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="" src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/fpzNxcu_oy1ZmpJu91d8t7O6w1k=/0x0:900x600/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/69325155/citizen_suf_security.0.jpg" /&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="evuFVS"&gt;This morning, &lt;em&gt;The Verge &lt;/em&gt;published a story about how Citizen — an app that appears to encourage vigilante justice — encouraged its users &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2021/5/21/22447446/citizen-app-internal-slack-palisades-fire-arson-bounty-manhunt-los-angeles"&gt;to hunt down &lt;em&gt;the wrong person&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;em&gt; &lt;/em&gt;and presumably bring them to justice, in the mistaken assumption that person had started the 1,158-acre Palisades wildfire in Los Angeles last week. The company offered a $30,000 bounty. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="gUHfZh"&gt;Now, we’re learning the same company is apparently planning to offer its own private security forces to users, &lt;a href="https://www.vice.com/en/article/v7evbx/citizen-app-private-security-leaked-emails"&gt;according to a new report from &lt;em&gt;Motherboard&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="oXziIE"&gt;In fact, one Citizen-branded patrol car has &lt;a href="https://twitter.com/brandonwenerd/status/1395045423958478849"&gt;already been spotted&lt;/a&gt; in the wild:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div id="ds8kB5"&gt;
&lt;blockquote class="twitter-tweet"&gt;
&lt;p lang="en" dir="ltr"&gt;Few things make you feel like you live in a bleak dystopian reality like a Citizen App patrol car that looks like a cop car.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Spotted by ⁦&lt;a href="https://twitter.com/magggggiiieeeee?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw"&gt;@magggggiiieeeee&lt;/a&gt;⁩ on...&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
